From 6d079ebebd7bfd23dba29145c65d87613e0a7f0e Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: AAP Rebuild <aap-rebuild-bot@localhost>
Date: Sat, 9 May 2026 11:15:55 +0300
Subject: [PATCH] patch: rebase Dockerfile.runner on quay.io/fitbeard/ansible-platform/awx-ee

Upstream's quay.io/ansible/ansible-runner:latest base is abandoned per
its quay.io repo description ('no longer maintained'): last build
2022-04-29, CentOS Stream 8 (EOL May 2024), Python 3.8 (EOL Oct 2024),
amd64-only.

quay.io/fitbeard/ansible-platform/awx-ee mirrors the actively-maintained quay.io/ansible/awx-ee
(rebuilt daily upstream, CentOS Stream 9, Python 3.9, multi-arch). It
already ships most of what the upstream Dockerfile installs:

  - ansible-runner / ansible-galaxy / pip3 on PATH
  - collections: awx.awx, kubernetes.core (versions newer than required)
  - pip:         awxkit, kubernetes

We install one collection ourselves: operator_sdk.util. It's the
canonical k8s_status module for ansible-operator workloads. The
runner's roles/job_runner/ has 11 references to
operator_sdk.util.k8s_status for updating CR status subresources;
without it the runner Job aborts with 'couldn't resolve module/action
operator_sdk.util.k8s_status'. (The upstream Dockerfile installs it via
`ansible-galaxy collection install -r requirements.yml`; we install
only the missing piece.)

The skipped 'openshift' pip package from upstream is a deprecated alias
for the 'kubernetes' python client (which awx-ee already has).

Paths are hardcoded to /home/runner (awx-ee's user is uid 1000 'runner'
with HOME=/home/runner) rather than ${HOME}: BuildKit's Dockerfile
parser doesn't substitute ENV inherited from the FROM image at parse
time, so bare ${HOME} raised UndefinedVar warnings and resolved to
empty (silently misplacing the role at /roles instead of /home/runner/roles).
---
 Dockerfile.runner | 28 ++++++++++++++++++++--------
 1 file changed, 20 insertions(+), 8 deletions(-)

diff --git a/Dockerfile.runner b/Dockerfile.runner
index 072375e..79c4ee4 100644
--- a/Dockerfile.runner
+++ b/Dockerfile.runner
@@ -1,12 +1,24 @@
-FROM quay.io/ansible/ansible-runner:latest
-ENV ANSIBLE_ROLES_PATH ${HOME}/roles
+FROM quay.io/fitbeard/ansible-platform/awx-ee:latest
 
-COPY requirements.yml ${HOME}/requirements.yml
+# awx-ee runs as user `runner` (uid 1000) with HOME=/home/runner. We
+# hardcode that path instead of `${HOME}` because Dockerfile-parse-time
+# substitution doesn't see ENV inherited from the FROM image, only ARG
+# and ENV declared in the current Dockerfile (BuildKit raises
+# UndefinedVar warnings on bare `${HOME}` here).
+ENV ANSIBLE_ROLES_PATH=/home/runner/roles
 
-RUN ansible-galaxy collection install -r ${HOME}/requirements.yml --force \
- && chmod -R ug+rwx ${HOME}/.ansible && mkdir -p ${HOME}/roles
+# awx-ee already provides ansible-runner, ansible-galaxy, python3, pip3,
+# the awx.awx + kubernetes.core collections (versions newer than
+# requirements.yml asks for), and the awxkit + kubernetes pip packages.
+#
+# What's missing from awx-ee is operator_sdk.util — the canonical
+# k8s_status implementation for ansible-operator workloads. The runner's
+# roles/job_runner/ has 11 references to operator_sdk.util.k8s_status
+# for updating CR status subresources. Install it explicitly here.
+# (This mirrors what upstream Dockerfile does via `-r requirements.yml`,
+# but we install only the missing piece to avoid noise.)
+RUN ansible-galaxy collection install operator_sdk.util:==0.5.0 \
+ && chmod -R ug+rwx /home/runner/.ansible
 
-RUN pip3 install awxkit kubernetes openshift
-
-COPY roles/job_runner ${HOME}/roles/job_runner
+COPY roles/job_runner /home/runner/roles/job_runner
 CMD ["ansible-runner", "run", "/runner", "--hosts", "localhost", "--role", "job_runner", "--role-skip-facts"]
